        <h1>LeetCode 1653: Minimum Deletions to Make String Balanced (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given a string s consisting only of characters 'a' and 'b'. You can delete any number of characters in s to make s balanced. s is balanced if there is no pair of indices (i, j) such that i &lt; j and s[i] = 'b' and s[j] = 'a'. Return the minimum number of deletions needed to make s balanced.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: s = "aababbab"<br/>
                Output: 2<br/>
                Explanation: You can either: Delete the characters at 0-indexed positions 2 and 6 ("aababbab" -&gt; "aaabbb"), or Delete the characters at 0-indexed positions 3 and 6 ("aababbab" -&gt; "aabbbb").<br/><br/>
                Input: s = "bbaaaaabb"<br/>
                Output: 2<br/>
                Explanation: The only solution is to delete the first two characters.<br/><br/>
                Input: s = "aaa"<br/>
                Output: 0<br/>
                Explanation: The string is already balanced.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int minimumDeletions(string s) {
        int n = s.length();
        int bCount = 0;  // Count of 'b' characters seen so far
        int deletions = 0;
        
        for (char c : s) {
            if (c == 'b') {
                bCount++;
            } else {
                // c == 'a'
                // Either delete this 'a' or delete all previous 'b's
                deletions = min(deletions + 1, bCount);
            }
        }
        
        return deletions;
    }
};</code></pre>
